# Product Summary

## Overview
This product is a desktop web app for hackathon founders preparing for high-stakes demo day pitches. It is not a general startup planning tool, CRM, or productivity dashboard. It is a focused rehearsal system for turning a rough project into a compelling pitch, pressure-testing it through adversarial Q&A, and generating a structured post-mortem for iteration.

The core product loop is:
1. Prepare the context.
2. Perform the pitch.
3. Survive the Q&A.
4. Review what broke.
5. Improve and retry.

The product should feel:
- Institutional
- Calm but high-stakes
- Analytical
- Credible
- Founder-grade
- Minimal, not flashy
- More like a serious review room than a generic AI chatbot app.

## Core User
The primary user is a hackathon founder who has already built something quickly and now needs help with:
- clarifying the idea,
- tailoring the pitch to the event,
- practicing delivery,
- surviving judge questions,
- and understanding how to improve before the final presentation.

## Core Value Proposition
The app helps founders rehearse demo day in a realistic workflow:
- capture project and hackathon context,
- record an opening pitch,
- enter a live-room style Q&A experience,
- receive a structured review,
- and continue learning through a follow-up coach interface.

This app is not about generating a pitch from scratch. It is about pressure-testing a pitch.

## Product Principles
- The workflow is narrow and opinionated.
- Primary navigation reflects phases, not features.
- The Room is the emotional center of the app.
- The Debrief is the main value artifact.
- Analytics and session history are secondary utility views, not part of the main journey.
- Avoid generic dashboard clutter and neon AI aesthetics.

